    a = 8, b = 20, c = 11  
    b − a = 12  
    α = 1 + 4 × (c − a)/(b − a) = 1 + 4 × (3/12) = 1 + 4 × 0.25 = 1 + 1 = 2  
    β = 1 + 4 × (b − c)/(b − a) = 1 + 4 × (9/12) = 1 + 4 × 0.75 = 1 + 3 = 4
    α = 2, β = 4

  2.Support of X
    [8, 20]

  3.f(x) = [(x − 8)^(1) (20 − x)^(3)] / [B(2,4) × (12)^(5)], for 8 ≤ x ≤ 20, else 0
    where B(2,4) = Γ(2)Γ(4)/Γ(6) = (1! × 3!)/5! = (1 × 6)/120 = 6/120 = 1/20
    So f(x) = 20 × (x − 8)(20 − x)^3 / 12^5

  4.Ω = [8, 20]  
    ℱ = Borel sets on [8, 20]  
    P(A) = ∫_A f(x) dx

  5.Random Variable X
    X(ω) = ω (identity mapping)

  6.E[X] = (a + 4c + b)/6 = (8 + 44 + 20)/6 = 72/6 = 12 days

  7.E[X] = 12  
    Var(X) = (E[X] − a)(b − E[X]) / 7 = (12 − 8)(20 − 12)/7 = (4 × 8)/7 = 32/7 ≈ 4.571 days²

  8.σ = √(32/7) ≈ √4.571 ≈ 2.138 days

  9.Triangular (Q5): mean = 20/3 ≈ 6.67 hours, σ ≈ 1.25 hours  
    PERT (Q6): mean = 12 days, σ ≈ 2.14 days  

    PERT gives more weight to the mode (c) and smoother tails. It's preferred when experts are more confident in the most likely estimate. Triangular is simpler but less smooth. PERT approximates a Beta distribution, which is more flexible and realistic for project time modeling.

